<task>
	<introduction><p>Note that the amount of radiation (energy) remains the same regardless of the radius of the sphere. That is a sphere with radius 1 and surface area <m>4\pi</m> has the same energy as a sphere with radius 2 and surface area <m>16\pi</m>.</p></introduction>
	<task><statement>
		<p>If the radiation is being emitted at an intensity of <m>5</m> Sieverts per hour (<quantity><unit base="sievert" /><per base="hour" /></quantity>), what amount of radiation will be hitting our 1 <quantity><unit base="meter" exp="2" /></quantity> person who is at a distance of 1 <quantity><unit base="meter" /></quantity> from the source?</p>
	</statement></task>
	<task><statement>
		<p>If the radiation is being emitted at an intensity of <m>5</m> Sieverts per hour (<quantity><unit base="sievert" /><per base="hour" /></quantity>), what amount of radiation will be hitting our 1 <quantity><unit base="meter" exp="2" /></quantity> person who is at a distance of 2 <quantity><unit base="meter" /></quantity> from the source?</p>
	</statement></task>
	<task><statement>
		<p>In general as the distance (radius) increases what happens to the amount of radiation absorbed by the person do? Increase/remain the same/decrease?</p>
	</statement></task>
</task>

