<task>
	<statement><p>The sphere with a floating radiation source is a good model for us to use when thinking through how distance impacts radiation levels because we can disregard complicating factors like the walls, floor, and ceiling of the room as long as a person is still directly exposed to the radiation source. Still, the relationship you found between radius and radiation holds true. With that in mind, answer the following questions.</p>

	<p>Let <m>I</m> stand for radiation experienced by the person, <m>r</m> stand for distance, and <m>k</m> be the constant of variation. Write an equation of variation representing the relationship between <m>I, r</m>, and <m>k</m>.</p></statement>

	<hint><p>Look back at your recent answers and the table you built. Is the formula you wrote logically consistent with these answers?  That is, if you plugged in the <m>r</m> with some constant value <m>k</m>, would you get the right answer for <m>I</m>?</p></hint>
</task>

